Date: 10/9/1841
Source: GBPP
Author:
Vol / Page: 1842 (No.569) 130
Edition:
Quote: The memorial [from Mr.Sinclair, Wellington] states that certain town lots ... had been advertised for sale by auction, but that several allotments, comprising some of the most valuable lands in the township, ... had been reserved from such sale ...; that these sections were to be paid for at the average price of half the town sections ...
Notes:  Villiers and Lefevre : Colonial Land and Emigration Office in GBPP

Date: 10/2/1841
Source: GBPP
Author:
Vol / Page: 1842 (No.569) 131
Edition:
Quote: By the Government advertisement for the sale of town lands at Auckland, it was stated that sections ... would be exposed to sale by auction, but we have since learned that several allotments, comprising some of the most valuable lands in the township, have been reserved from such sale ...; and that these sections are to be paid for, not according to the price ... of the less valuable lots in their vicinity ... but at the average price of half the town sections ...
Notes: D.Sinclair and others, Wellington to Sir George Gipps in GBPP

Date: 0/0/1859
Source: Story of New Zealand, The
Author: THOMSON
Vol / Page: 2/60
Edition:
Quote: At Auckland the people were living on the government expenditure, and awaited the arrival of immigrants to occupy the houses they had built, and re-purchase the town lots they had bought.
